{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":25657,"record_hash":"sha256:8645dee8c6a3a61c1df9db76bd0b807f1c7ec23b579577fd0210554dfabf01d0","timestamp":"2026-05-11T10:07:51.279Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"Yes: for large list entries, read access may now need to hit Git objects.\n\nBut I don’t think that violates the intended semantic. It means SQLite is still the index/cache of metadata structure, while large values can live as Git blobs with SQLite storing the object id. That is already how GitMeta appears to model large values: `list_values` has `is_git_ref`, and read paths like `list_entries` resolve those refs when a repo is attached.\n\nThe tradeoff is:\n\n- SQLite stays much smaller.\n- Large transcript records become Git-addressed content.\n- Reading the full transcript needs both SQLite and the repo object database.\n- Reading indexes/dedupe stays SQLite-only, because `record-hashes` lives in `set_values`.\n\nFor the agentlog hot path, this is good: repeated capture only reads the hash set from SQLite, not the transcript blobs. For future browsing/export, reading the transcript timeline will resolve Git blobs, but that seems acceptable because the transcript itself is content meant to be serialized/shared through Git eventually.\n\nThe semantic I’d be careful about is not “SQLite cache” broadly, but “can every local read work without Git object access?” With blob-backed large values, no. If we want SQLite to be a complete self-contained local cache of all values, then blob refs are the wrong direction. But for GitMeta as shareable metadata over Git, blob-backed large values feel consistent.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-11T10:07:51.279Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}